  <mainDescription>&lt;a id=&quot;Top&quot; name=&quot;Top&quot;>&lt;/a>&lt;a id=&quot;XE_asset_consumption___guidelines_for_applying_RUP&quot;&#xD;
name=&quot;XE_asset_consumption___guidelines_for_applying_RUP&quot;>&lt;/a> &#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    &lt;a id=&quot;Introduction&quot; name=&quot;Introduction&quot;>&lt;/a>Introduction&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Most projects should include asset consumption as part of their development process, in order to obtain the benefits&#xD;
    that come from reuse.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    &lt;a id=&quot;PM&quot; name=&quot;PM&quot;>&lt;/a>Project Management&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The impacts of asset consumption on Project Management are:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Asset reuse is factored into cost, schedule, and risks&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Build vs. reuse decisions are supported by effective use of information provided in reuse libraries&lt;br />&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    &lt;a id=&quot;env&quot; name=&quot;env&quot;>&lt;/a>Environment&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Before asset-based development tasks can be performed, an environment must be set up that supports these tasks. In most&#xD;
    cases, this needs to be an environment that has broader scope than a single project, and is therefore the&#xD;
    responsibility of the organization-level reuse program.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The individual project needs access to this environment. This typically includes access to one or more &lt;a&#xD;
    class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../../practice.mgmt.asset_based_dev.base-ibm/workproducts/repository_BBA87BE5.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;{634E94FE-A1C0-4B66-94C0-4D91B3CADB90}&quot;>Artifact: Asset Repository&lt;/a>. This is closely related to more generic&#xD;
    artifacts (e.g. Project Repository) and to the setup of the project's Configuration and Change Management environment.&#xD;
    The main difference is that the asset library is typically not under the control of the individual project, but is&#xD;
    managed at the organizational level.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The delivery process should be updated to include the project's asset-based development tooling. For more information&#xD;
    on tooling to support asset-based development, see &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../../practice.mgmt.asset_based_dev_gov.base-ibm/guidances/guidelines/selecting_asset_based_development_tools_BBBA0116.html&quot;&#xD;
     guid=&quot;1.2013990160057124E-304&quot;>Guideline: Selecting Asset-Based Development Tools&lt;/a>.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The project-specific guidelines may also need to be modified to reflect the refined workflows. For more information on&#xD;
    preparing project-specific guidelines, see&amp;nbsp;&lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../../practice.mgmt.asset_based_dev_gov.base-ibm/guidances/guidelines/preparing_project_specific_reuse_guidelines_1D014F26.html&quot;&#xD;
     guid=&quot;8.994384407791297E-306&quot;>Guideline: Preparing Project-Specific Reuse Guidelines&lt;/a>.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    &lt;a id=&quot;ccm&quot; name=&quot;ccm&quot;>&lt;/a>Configuration and Change Management&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    There are general tasks that apply to consumption of any Reusable Asset. This includes locating a suitable asset (&lt;a&#xD;
    class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot; href=&quot;./../../../practice.mgmt.asset_based_dev.base-ibm/tasks/search_asset_C29C6178.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;{81DC995B-5930-4F2B-B574-9805136CE94A}&quot;>Task: Search Asset&lt;/a>), applying the asset (&lt;a&#xD;
    class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot; href=&quot;./../../../practice.mgmt.asset_based_dev.base-ibm/tasks/use_asset_8AC5E42C.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;{7E587465-5AF6-4E91-8869-1193C7577C25}&quot;>Task: Use Asset&lt;/a>), providing feedback on the asset (&lt;a&#xD;
    class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../../practice.mgmt.asset_based_dev.base-ibm/tasks/provide_asset_feedback_6AA5DD76.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;{E642B808-1646-45AD-AEFA-D4595C8D0FEB}&quot;>Task: Provide Asset Feedback&lt;/a>), and possibly identifying other&#xD;
    potentially Reusable Assets (&lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../../practice.mgmt.asset_based_dev.base-ibm/tasks/conduct_recurring_problem_analysis_2FBA07F4.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;_Xih4kPCtEdquxKT1X5kJ4g&quot;>Task: Conduct Recurring Problem Analysis&lt;/a>).&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    &lt;a id=&quot;other&quot; name=&quot;other&quot;>&lt;/a>Other Disciplines&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    All the other disciplines include asset reuse concerns. For example:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        In the Requirements discipline, there may be specific requirements to reuse specific artifacts. For example, there&#xD;
        may be design constraints to use a particular reference architecture. More often, reuse is a means to meet&#xD;
        requirements with cost savings and lower risk. Reuse must be factored into the prioritization and scope management&#xD;
        of requirements.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The Analysis and Design discipline has a strong reuse focus, reflected by the practice of Use Component&#xD;
        Architectures, and by incorporating existing design elements. This in turn affects Implementation, Test, and&#xD;
        Deployment.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul></mainDescription>
